  <subsection xml:id="subsec-product-to-sum">
    <title>Product to Sum Formulas</title>
    <p>
    
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-product-to-sum">
      <title>Product to Sum Formulas</title><idx><h>product-to-sum formulas</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <me>
            \sin\alpha\cos\beta=\frac{1}{2}[\sin(\alpha+\beta)+\sin(\alpha-\beta)]
          </me>
          <me>
            \cos\alpha\sin\beta=\frac{1}{2}[\sin(\alpha+\beta)-\sin(\alpha-\beta)]
          </me>
          <me>
            \cos\alpha\cos\beta=\frac{1}{2}[\cos(\alpha+\beta)+\cos(\alpha-\beta)]
          </me>
          <me>
            \sin\alpha\sin\beta=\frac{1}{2}[\cos(\alpha-\beta)-\cos(\alpha+\beta)]
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We add the addition and subtraction formulas for cosine:
        <md>
          <mrow> \cos(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow> +\cos(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow>\hline </mrow>
          <mrow> \cos(\alpha+\beta)+\cos(\alpha-\beta) \amp = 2\cos\alpha\cos\beta </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by 2, we get
        <me>
          \frac{1}{2}[\cos(\alpha+\beta)+\cos(\alpha-\beta)]=\cos\alpha\cos\beta
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, we add the addition and subtraction formulas for sine:
        <md>
          <mrow> \sin(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow> +\sin(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta-\cos\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow>\hline </mrow>
          <mrow> \sin(\alpha+\beta)+\sin(\alpha-\beta) \amp = 2\sin\alpha\cos\beta </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by 2, we get
        <me>
          \frac{1}{2}[\sin(\alpha+\beta)+\sin(\alpha-\beta)]=\sin\alpha\cos\beta
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, we subtract the addition and subtraction formulas for sine:
        <md>
          <mrow> \sin(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow> -\sin(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta-\cos\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow>\hline </mrow>
          <mrow> \sin(\alpha+\beta)-\sin(\alpha-\beta) \amp = 2\sin\beta\cos\alpha </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by 2, we get
        <me>
          \frac{1}{2}[\sin(\alpha+\beta)-\sin(\alpha-\beta)]=\sin\beta\cos\alpha
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Finally, we subtract the addition and subtraction formulas for cosine:
        <md>
          <mrow> \cos(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow> -\cos(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
          <mrow>\hline </mrow>
          <mrow> \cos(\alpha-\beta)-\cos(\alpha+\beta) \amp = 2\sin\alpha\sin\beta </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by 2, we get
        <me>
          \frac{1}{2}[\cos(\alpha-\beta)-\cos(\alpha+\beta)]=\sin\alpha\sin\beta
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Express the product of <m>\cos(2x)\cos(5x)</m> as a sum or difference of sine and cosine with no products.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Using the formula we get
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos(2x)\cos(5x)\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\cos(2x+5x)+\cos(2x-5x)]</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\cos(7x)+\cos(-3x)]</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Since cosine is even, <m>\cos(-3x)=\cos(3x)</m>.
          Thus,
          <me>
            \cos(2x)\cos(5x)=\frac{1}{2}[\cos(7x)+\cos(3x)]
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sum-to-product">
    <title>Sum to Product Formulas</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-sum-to-product">
      <title>Sum-to-Product Formula</title><idx><h>sum-to-product formula</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin\alpha+\sin\beta\amp = 2\sin\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\sin\alpha-\sin\beta\amp = 2\cos\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right)\sin\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\cos\alpha+\cos\beta\amp = 2\cos\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\cos\alpha-\cos\beta\amp = -2\sin\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right)\sin\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We first let <m>\alpha=\frac{u+v}{2}</m> and <m>\beta=\frac{u-v}{2}</m>.
        Then
        <me>
          \alpha+\beta=\frac{u+v}{2}+\frac{u-v}{2}=\frac{2u}{2}=u
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \alpha-\beta=\frac{u+v}{2}-\frac{u-v}{2}=\frac{2v}{2}=v
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Substituting these values for <m>\alpha</m>,
        <m>\beta</m>, <m>\alpha+\beta</m>,
        and <m>\alpha-\beta</m> into the Product-to-Sum Formulas, we get
        <md>
          <mrow>\sin\left(\frac{u+v}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{u-v}{2}\right)\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\sin(u)+\sin(v)]</mrow>
          <mrow>\cos\left(\frac{u+v}{2}\right)\sin\left(\frac{u-v}{2}\right)\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\sin(u)-\sin(v)]</mrow>
          <mrow>\cos\left(\frac{u+v}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{u-v}{2}\right)\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\cos(u)+\cos(v)]</mrow>
          <mrow>\sin\left(\frac{u+v}{2}\right)\sin\left(\frac{u-v}{2}\right)\amp = \frac{1}{2}[\cos(v)-\cos(u)]</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Multiplying both sides by 2 and replacing <m>u</m> with <m>\alpha</m> and <m>v</m> with <m>\beta</m> we end up with the Sum-to-Product Formula. (multiply the last equation by -1)
      </p>
      <p>
        ***reword***
      </p>
    </proof>
